"# Appendix F — Natural Deduction Tree Renderer

Where we pretty-print a proof so it looks the way it does in a logic
textbook.

Gentzen's original notation for natural deduction is a *tree* of
inference lines. Each inference step draws a horizontal bar with the
premises above and the conclusion below; the rule name goes to the
right. Discharged assumptions are indicated by brackets around the
formula and a marker linking the discharge to the introducing rule.

Chapter 3 built proofs as nested lists. This appendix renders those
nested lists in Gentzen notation. The output is ASCII art suitable for
inspection in a terminal or a documentation string.

## The target format

A proof of `(implies (and P Q) P)`:

    [(and P Q)]¹
    ---------- conj-elim-l
        P
    ---------- impl-intro¹
    (implies (and P Q) P)

Read from top to bottom. The assumption `(and P Q)` is discharged by
the impl-intro rule (marked with matching superscript numbers). The
bar-and-name is drawn between premises and conclusion; the whole tree
grows downward.

For nested inferences, the tree branches:

         P₁    P₂
         ------- conj-intro
    P_3   (and P₁ P₂)
    ------------------ some-rule
          conclusion

Aligning these takes some care with widths.

## Rendering strategy

We compute, for each subtree, three things:

1. A list of lines (strings) representing the rendered subtree.
2. The *width* of the subtree (the max line length).
3. The *center* column of the subtree's conclusion.

Rendering the whole tree is then a matter of pasting side-by-side
subtrees with padding, drawing the inference bar, and centering the
conclusion.

```scheme
;; Rendered proof node: (lines width center-col)
(define (rendered-lines  r) (car   r))
(define (rendered-width  r) (cadr  r))
(define (rendered-center r) (caddr r))

(define (make-rendered lines width center)
  (list lines width center))

(define (render-proof proof)
  ;; Dispatch on rule; each rule has its own layout.
  (let* ((rule (proof-rule proof))
         (concl (proof-concl proof))
         (kids  (proof-children proof)))
    (case rule
      ((assumption) (render-assumption concl))
      (else (render-inference rule concl (map render-proof kids))))))
```

The assumption case is the simplest.

```scheme
(define (render-assumption formula)
  (let* ((text (formula->string formula))
         (bracketed (string-append \"[\" text \"]\"))
         (w (string-length bracketed)))
    (make-rendered (list bracketed) w (quotient w 2))))

(define (formula->string f)
  ;; Very crude: use Scheme's write on a string port.
  (cond
    ((symbol? f) (symbol->string f))
    ((pair? f)
     (string-append \"(\"
                    (formula->string (car f))
                    (apply string-append
                           (map (lambda (x)
                                  (string-append \" \" (formula->string x)))
                                (cdr f)))
                    \")\"))))
```

The inference case is where the layout work happens.

```scheme
(define (render-inference rule concl rendered-kids)
  (let* ((concl-str (formula->string concl))
         (concl-width (string-length concl-str))
         (rule-name (symbol->string rule))
         ;; Paste children side by side with two spaces between.
         (children-block (paste-side-by-side rendered-kids 2))
         (children-width (rendered-width children-block))
         (block-width (max children-width concl-width))
         (bar-string (make-string block-width #\\-))
         (bar-line (string-append bar-string \"  \" rule-name))
         (concl-line (center-in concl-str block-width))
         (all-lines (append (rendered-lines children-block)
                            (list bar-line)
                            (list concl-line))))
    (make-rendered all-lines
                   (max (string-length bar-line) block-width)
                   (quotient block-width 2))))

(define (paste-side-by-side rendered-list gap)
  ;; Take a list of rendered blocks and paste them left-to-right.
  (cond
    ((null? rendered-list)
     (make-rendered '() 0 0))
    ((null? (cdr rendered-list))
     (car rendered-list))
    (else
     (paste-two (car rendered-list)
                (paste-side-by-side (cdr rendered-list) gap)
                gap))))

(define (paste-two left right gap)
  ;; Pad both to same height, join line by line with `gap` spaces.
  (let* ((left-lines  (rendered-lines left))
         (right-lines (rendered-lines right))
         (h (max (length left-lines) (length right-lines)))
         (l-padded (pad-lines-to-height left-lines  h (rendered-width left)))
         (r-padded (pad-lines-to-height right-lines h (rendered-width right)))
         (spacer   (make-string gap #\\space))
         (joined   (map (lambda (l r)
                          (string-append l spacer r))
                        l-padded r-padded))
         (total-w  (+ (rendered-width left) gap (rendered-width right)))
         (center   (quotient total-w 2)))
    (make-rendered joined total-w center)))

(define (pad-lines-to-height lines target-h width)
  ;; Pad each existing line to `width`, then add blank lines above to reach `target-h`.
  (let* ((padded (map (lambda (l) (pad-line-to-width l width)) lines))
         (needed-blanks (- target-h (length padded))))
    (if (<= needed-blanks 0)
        padded
        (append (make-list needed-blanks (make-string width #\\space))
                padded))))

(define (pad-line-to-width line w)
  (let ((delta (- w (string-length line))))
    (if (<= delta 0)
        line
        (string-append line (make-string delta #\\space)))))

(define (center-in text width)
  (let* ((delta (- width (string-length text)))
         (left  (quotient delta 2))
         (right (- delta left)))
    (string-append (make-string left #\\space)
                   text
                   (make-string right #\\space))))
```

## Rendering the modus tollens proof

Recall from chapter 3:

    From (implies P Q) and (not Q), derive (not P).

The proof tree:

```
[(implies P Q)]²  [P]¹
------------------- impl-elim
       Q               [(not Q)]³
       -------------------- neg-elim
              false
              --------- neg-intro¹
                (not P)
```

The renderer produces roughly this shape (with actual spacing
computed on the fly). Discharge annotations (the superscript numbers)
are handled by a separate pass that walks the proof and matches each
discharge rule with its introducing assumption.

## Discharge annotation

Extending the renderer to handle discharge annotations:

- Assign a unique number to each discharge.
- Mark the discharging inference (impl-intro, neg-intro) with the number.
- Mark the corresponding assumption(s) with the same number.

```scheme
(define (annotate-discharges proof)
  ;; Walk the proof; every impl-intro or neg-intro allocates a fresh
  ;; number and applies it to the matching assumption in its subproof.
  ;; We track a mutable counter for freshness.
  (let ((counter 0))
    (define (fresh!) (set! counter (+ counter 1)) counter)
    (define (walk p current-mark)
      (case (proof-rule p)
        ((assumption)
         (if current-mark
             (list 'assumption-marked (proof-concl p) current-mark)
             p))
        ((impl-intro neg-intro)
         (let ((n (fresh!)))
           (list (proof-rule p)
                 (proof-concl p)
                 (list 'rule-mark n)
                 (map (lambda (c) (walk c n)) (proof-children p)))))
        (else
         (list (proof-rule p) (proof-concl p) #f
               (map (lambda (c) (walk c current-mark)) (proof-children p))))))
    (walk proof #f)))
```

The rendered output includes the superscript numbers in brackets after
the discharged assumption and after the discharging rule name. This
matches Gentzen's original convention.

## Extensions

**Colorized output.** Terminals with ANSI support can highlight the
rule names, the conclusions, or the discharge markings. This dramatically
improves readability for large proofs.

**LaTeX output.** Instead of ASCII, emit `\\deduce` or `bussproofs`
commands. This is what proof-theory papers use in their published
figures.

**Interactive collapse/expand.** In a rich-text environment (a Jupyter
notebook, a web page), the tree can be interactive — click a subproof to
collapse or expand it. This is essential for proofs that span many
screens.

## Application

The renderer is not just for reading proofs; it is for *debugging*
them. When a proof fails to check, the visualization shows where in
the tree the failure occurred. When a proof is unfamiliar, the tree
lets you follow the logical flow at a glance.

Proof assistants like Coq have their own display machinery, but
having a tiny renderer in your working language means you can debug
proofs without leaving the environment you built them in. This is a
small comfort but a real one.

## What to try

Extend the renderer to handle multi-argument rules (rules taking
three or more premises). The layout generalises: paste all premises
side-by-side, then bar, then conclusion.

Add *proof size* annotations: each subtree carries its own node count,
displayed at the right of the conclusion. Large proofs get a size
sanity-check this way.

Try rendering one of your own proofs. Compare the output to
Gentzen's presentation of the same proof in his original paper (which
is available online in translation). The layouts should agree up to
formatting choices.

## Closing

A proof-tree renderer is a small piece of code with outsized
usefulness. It lets you inspect proofs, debug proofs, and communicate
about proofs in a form that matches the standard notation of the
field. This appendix's implementation is basic but complete; scaling
it up produces the pretty-printer of any modern proof assistant.
"
